==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*fadēr'', from Indo-European ''*ph₂ter-''.

:''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[feder]], Old Saxon [[fadar]] (Dutch [[vader]]), Old High German [[fater]] (German [[Vater]]), Old Franconian [[fader]], Old Norse [[faðir]] (Swedish [[fader#Swedish|fader]]), Gothic [[𐍆𐌰𐌳𐌰𐍂]].

:''Indo-European cognates:'' Avestan ''pitā'' (''pitar-''), Greek [[πατήρ]], Latin [[pater]], Armenian [[հայր]], Old Irish [[athir]] (Breton [[ualart]]), Tocharian A ''pācar''.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'fædeɹ/

===Noun===
'''fæder''' ''m''
# a [[father]]
#:''Ðis is se ilca God, ðone fæderas cuðon'': this is the same god, whom your fathers knew.  (''Legend of St Andrew'')

